        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>495 Lexington Av.<lb/>
                New York&#44; 1st. Dec. 1885.<lb/></p>
            <p>Dear Sir&#44;<lb/></p>
            <p>I have not sufficient time today<lb/> to reply lengthily to your esteemed commu&#45;<lb/>nication of  26<hi rend="sup">th</hi> ult&#44; but you may rely on<lb/> my doing what I can in furtherance of yr.<lb/> project&#44; for religious education is a matter<lb/> which has been nearest my heart from<lb/> early manhood. At the same time&#44; you must<lb/> take into consideration that I have but <lb/> lately come into public life&#44; and therefore<lb/> cannot be expected to have much influence.<lb/> The work&#44; you will also admit&#44; is a great<lb/> one&#44; and cannot be accomplished alone by<lb/> our congregation&#44; tho&#39; started under our<lb/> auspices. It will require agitation &#44; and<lb/> a zealous endeavour on the part of others<lb/> as well&#44; to infuse enthusiasm in its favor<lb/> in the hearts of all those who still believe<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>in the mission of Israel&#44; and that we are all&#44;<lb/> besides&#44; responsible for one another. Ignorance<lb/> of our holy faith is&#44; I believe&#44; the principal<lb/> cause of the present indifference to religion<lb/> on the part of many&#59; and&#44; unfortunately&#44; most<lb/> of their leading men have been of the destruc&#45;<lb/>tive kind which pander to the desire for lax&#45;<lb/>ity&#44; a natural inclination in the hearts of<lb/> the thoughtless. Therefore it is only by the<lb/> faithful coming boldly before the public&#44;<lb/> with trust in God&#44; and without fear of a pos&#45;<lb/>sible failure&#44; in defense of all that should<lb/> be sacred to them&#44; that any good can be at&#45;<lb/>tained. The eyes of our brethren must be<lb/> opened to the wanton profanation of the Holy<lb/> Name&#44; which has become common&#44; that they<lb/> may understand it as such&#59; and to the disre&#45;<lb/>pute into which these destructives are bring&#45;<lb/>ing the whole house of Israel. I have al&#45;<lb/>ready shown your letter to two of my col&#45;<lb/>leagues and to our Minister&#59; and as the<lb/> Board will meet on Thursday evening&#44; I<lb/></p> 
                
                <pb n="3"/>
            <p>shall then&#44; D.V.&#91;&#63;&#93; bring the subject before the<lb/> meeting. Meanwhile I ask your consent to<lb/> give your letter further circulation. Other<lb/> ministers could give us their moral sup&#45;<lb/>port&#44; even if their congregation be unable<lb/> to furnish financial means. Rev. A. P. Mendes<lb/> and Rev. M.deSola would doubtless aid us<lb/> in this respect. Dr. Schneeberger of Baltimore<lb/> is also orthodox&#44; I believe&#59; and it seems to me<lb/> that we should have a meeting at which<lb/> such gentlemen&#44; including the learned and pi&#45;<lb/>ous of all congregations that may be willing<lb/> to cooperate with us&#44; could be present.<lb/></p>
            <p>No doubt you will keep the ball in motion.<lb/>
                Truly yours&#44;<lb/>
                David M. Piza.<lb/></p>
                
            <p>Rev. S. Morais&#44;<lb/>
                546 N. 5<hi rend="sup">th</hi> St.<lb/>
                Philadelphia.<lb/></p>
            </body>
